Here is the analysis of the admin API endpoints under the cms admin blueprint, including the full request paths (with prefixes) and the allowed HTTP methods inferred from the code.

Key prefix reasoning
- cms blueprint is mounted at /cms
- admin blueprint inside cms is mounted at /admin
- Therefore, every admin endpoint path starts with /cms/admin

Endpoints and method/verb details

1) Path: /cms/admin/permission
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: True
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses @admin_api.route("/permission") with no methods specified, defaulting to GET.

2) Path: /cms/admin/users
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: True
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses @admin_api.route("/users") with no methods specified, default GET.

3) Path: /cms/admin/user/{uid}/password
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: False
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: False
- PUT: True
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["PUT"].

4) Path: /cms/admin/user/{uid}
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: False
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: False
- PUT: False
- DELETE: True
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["DELETE"].

5) Path: /cms/admin/group/all
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: True
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["GET"].

6) Path: /cms/admin/group/{gid}
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: True
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: True
- DELETE: True
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["GET"] (for get_group) and later also PUT/DELETE (for update_group/delete_group) on the same path.

7) Path: /cms/admin/group
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: False
- POST: True
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: False
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["POST"].

8) Path: /cms/admin/permission/dispatch/batch
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: False
- POST: True
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: False
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["POST"].

9) Path: /cms/admin/permission/remove
- All methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: False
- POST: True
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: False
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False
- Rationale: route uses methods=["POST"].

Explanation
- The full paths above include the global prefixes: /cms (from cms blueprint) and /admin (from admin blueprint inside cms).
- For endpoints without an explicit methods list, Flask defaults to GET. Therefore, GET is allowed for those, and HEAD is typically handled by Flask automatically for GET routes.
- There is no endpoint in the provided code that declares all HTTP methods (i.e., a catch-all like methods=["GET","POST","PUT","PATCH","DELETE","OPTIONS","HEAD"]). Hence, All methods acceptable is False for every endpoint listed.
- HEAD is considered acceptable when GET is allowed for that route (either explicitly or via Flask’s default HEAD handling). For routes that do not include GET, HEAD is not provided by default in Flask, hence False there.
- OPTIONS is automatically handled by Flask (and reinforced by the CORS setup in apply_cors), so it is effectively acceptable for all endpoints (thus True for all listed).
- PATCH is not used in any route, so False for all endpoints.

If you’d like, I can present this as a compact OpenAPI-ready mapping or generate an OpenAPI skeleton with the above paths and methods.
